  1. Scatterplot (Alcohol vs. Total Crashes)
In [9]:
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x="alcohol", y="total")
plt.title("Scatterplot of Alcohol vs. Total Crashes")
plt.xlabel("Alcohol Consumption")
plt.ylabel("Total Crashes")
plt.show()

INFERENCE: There is a positive correlation between alcohol consumption and the total number of crashes meaning that higher the alcohol consumption, the increased amount of car crashes

  1. Boxplot (Insurance Premiums)
In [10]:
sns.boxplot(data=df, x="ins_premium")
plt.title("Boxplot of Insurance Premiums")
plt.xlabel("Insurance Premiums")
plt.show()

INFERENCE: The box plot is negetively skewed suggesting that most of the insurance premiums are relatively high with a few policyholders having exceptionally low premiums.

INFERENCE: The heatmap displays the correlation between numerical variables in the dataset. Total crashes with alcohol has strong positive correlation and with ins_premium has the strongest negetive correlation

  1. Line plot (Total Crashes by State)
In [28]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

sns.lineplot(data=df, x='abbrev', y='total')
plt.title("Line Plot of Total Crashes by State")
plt.xlabel("State (Abbreviation)")
plt.ylabel("Total Crashes")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()

INFERENCE: The line plot shows a visual representation of how the total number of crashes varies across states. States with higher values on the y-axis have experienced more total crashes, while states with lower values have fewer crashes.

  1. Countplot (Number of Speeding Fatalities by State)

plt.title("Countplot of Speeding Fatalities by State")

plt.ylabel("Count")

INFERENCE: Countplot compares the count of speeding and non-speeding fatalities by state and displays it.
